Date: Wed 23 My 2018 00:00 IST
Source: The Telegraph [edited]
https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/north-east/12-die-of-aes-je-in-assam-232407


Altogether 12 people have died of acute encephalitis syndrome (AES) in Assam this year [2018].

Among the deaths, 3 were confirmed as Japanese encephalitis (JE) and another was caused by scrub typhus. But the Assam health department said it could not identify what really led to the deaths of the other 8 persons though they all showed symptoms of AES.

Health department officials said this year [2018], 29 Japanese encephalitis cases and 149 AES cases have been reported in Assam. A majority of the cases are from Dibrugarh which recorded 17 Japanese encephalitis cases and 51 AES cases.

The National Health Mission official in Guwahati, Umesh Phangso, said, "It is a national problem. It is difficult to diagnose the disease."

In Assam, 10 districts, namely Dhemaji, Tinsukia, Golaghat, Dibrugarh, Sivasagar, Jorhat, Lakhimpur, Sonitpur, Barpeta, and Odalguri have a high prevalence of JE and AES.

"The Dibrugarh-based Regional Medical Research Centre this year [2018] named 5 districts from the 10 "most prevalent" ones.

Those 5 districts are Tinsukia, Dibrugarh, Sivsagar, Jorhat, and Lakhimpur. We have given more stress in those 5 districts to control the disease," Phangso said.

Among the 3 deaths due to Japanese encephalitis, 2 persons, including a minor, had been vaccinated. Phangso said the 2 persons who died in Dibrugarh were vaccinated in 2016.

"We have ordered an inquiry. It could be that the vaccination was not carried out properly," Phangso said.

In 2017, nearly 17 percent of the deaths in the state was because of Japanese encephalitis. Of the 604 cases of confirmed last year [2017], 87 patients died.

Phangso said according to experts, all those cases may not be Japanese encephalitis but could be some other disease. Japanese encephalitis is most prevalent from May to September.

[Byline: Manash Pratim Dutta]

