Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Japanese encephalitis virus (JEV) transmission season is just beginning in northeastern India, including Assam state. As is often the case, a minority of AES cases are due to JEV infections. It is difficult to explain the deaths of individuals vaccinated against JEV in 2016. If the vaccine is killed virus, protective immunity may be of shorter duration than live, attenuated vaccines would provide. The etiology of AES has been unclear but debated in the past decade. A recent publication of investigations conducted during the 2014 and 2015 AES outbreaks indicated that scrub typhus, caused by _Orientia tsutsugamushi_, was the etiology in about 60 percent of those AES cases. In the report above, there is just one case of scrub typhus.

As noted in many earlier posts, the determination of the etiology or etiologies of AES has been confusing and elusive. Various etiological agents have been proposed in recent years as responsible for AES cases. AES has continued to be attributed to a variety of etiologies, including Reye syndrome-like disease, possible enterovirus infection from polluted water, heat stroke, lychee fruit consumption and scrub typhus (_O. tsutsugamushi_). Recently, scrub typhus has been implicated in many AES cases. One hopes that these findings may stimulate prospective studies by ICMR (Indian Council of Medical Research) and other scientists as the season for occurrence of encephalitis cases in children is now beginning in northeastern India and many cases of encephalitis in children are likely to occur again this year (2018).

Maps of India can be accessed at http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/india/india-political-map.htm and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5812921,299; an Assam district map at can be accessed at https://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/assam/assam-district.htm - Mod.TY]
